  "A number that is always between one and ten": "",
  "The decimal form of any very large number value": "",
  "A power of 10 means 10 multiplied by itself a given number of times. For example, 10³ = 10 × 10 × 10 = 1,000. Powers of 10 form the basis for scientific notation.": "",
  "What is a base in scientific notation?": "",
  "The number 10, which is raised to a power in the notation": "",
  "The lowest digit that appears in the coefficient value": "",
  "The starting point of a measurement on a number line": "",
  "The bottom of a fraction in a mathematical expression": "",
  "In scientific notation, the base is always 10. The notation takes the form coefficient × 10ⁿ, where 10 is the base and n is the exponent.": "",
  "What does 'compact form' mean when describing scientific notation?": "",
  "Writing numbers using more digits than the standard form": "",
  "Rounding a number to the nearest whole number integer": "",
  "A shortened way of writing a number that uses fewer digits": "",
  "Using only fractions to represent very large number values": "",
  "Compact form means a shorter, more concise way of writing a number. Scientific notation is compact because it replaces many zeros with a power of 10. For example, 0.000000045 becomes 4.5 × 10⁻⁸.": "",
